Understanding Key Performance Indicators (KPIâ€™s)

Bernard Ade


Key performance indicators are instrumental to any organization interested in implementing a high performance culture. KPIâ€™s are metrics that tracks a team ability to accomplish goals. Although KPIâ€™s otherwise known as metrics isnâ€™t a new concept, it is surprisingly ignored by many organizations. From my experiences working with several enterprises, Iâ€™ve observed how this neglect often exposes a lot of weakneses that compromises performance. Without KPIâ€™s, how do you measure productivity and communicate goals effectively? KPIâ€™s are necessary to galvanize an army of employees armed with the information they need to achieve optimal performance.

Consider the case of a manager in the driver seat with his/her team as passengers. The vehicles dashboard is akin to a KPI with gauges informing the team with the state of affairs of their business unit. Suppose the pre-occupied manager takes an eye of the ball for a moment, one can take comfort in knowing that a team member can spot potential danger such as the vehicle running low on fuel considering rest stops are distanced 20 miles apart. With KPIâ€™s organizations can establish transparency which helps to improve communication and foster responsibility.

Defining KPIâ€™s.

When it comes to defining KPIâ€™s, there are good and bad metrics. Eric Ries in the book â€œLean Analyticsâ€ refers to bad metrics as vanity metrics. Bad metrics exists only to boost the ego and rarely drives the business or produce actionable insights. Here is a quote from Lean Analytics:

A good metric changes the way you behave. This is by far the most important criterion for a metric: what will you do differently based on changes in a metric?

Defining good metrics involves creating a vision and strategy along which your company competes. For instance, Toyota once implemented a strategy that placed safety and health on top of its agenda to revolutionize their manufactuing processes. During meetings, managers gather daily to discuss metrics focused on safety and health issues. Turns out this strategy yielded tremendous impact on daily production and kept employees safer from injury occurencies. In a nutshell, metrics should align behind a mission to influence employees behavior towards positive changes.

Developing KPIâ€™s?

Developing KPIâ€™s is a lot like building a sports scoreboard. For instance, a scoreboard maintains a collection of different stats such as scores, remaining fouls, time, timeouts etc. In a business case, the sport stats and scoreboard is akin to the KPI components and dashboard. A KPI component is a unit measure of a business process such as revenue, units sold, customers etc. A dashboard is a collection of those KPI components positioned to broadcast valuable insights to a business unit. The are many statistics available to build a KPI component, here are a few:

Metric - define a metric that is bound to change behaviour and drive action.

Data - gather data relevant to the business process.

Frequency - establish how often you want to track and monitor a KPI activity. i.e weekly or monthly.

Counting - There are two types of counting relevant here, How Many and How Much. How much communicates quantities that are measured rather than counted. How many communicates countable objects.

Histograms - histograms are useful for understanding how many of how much of a quantitative variable.

Ratios - ratios are useful for comparing relative amounts.

Sorting - sorting is useful for arranging information in a purposeful order for further analysis.

Average - average is useful for summarizing a bunch of numbers by one single digit to get a sense of central tendency.
